The plaintiff replied that his men were in pursuit of a buck in their common chase, where they and all the country could hunt the buck, and demanded that the defendant’s lord should corne and claim his warren. Afterwards a monk of the abbot carne and produced a charter which granted the abbey of St. Albans warren in all its demesne lands in England. Nevertheless, the court declared that the defendant should be in mercy, on the ground that the buck was not a beast of the warren.
